'''Crossing the Rubicon''' is a [[metaphor]] for deliberately proceeding past a [[point of no return]].  The phrase originates with [[Julius Caesar]]'s invasion of [[Ancient Rome]] when, on [[January 10]], [[49 BC]], he led his army across the [[Rubicon]] river in violation of law, hence making [[Caesar's civil war|conflict]] inevitable.  The phrase has been used in many places: 
*part of a speech by [[Pieter Willem Botha|President Botha]] of [[South Africa]] during the 80's referring to the [[History of South Africa in the apartheid era#State_of_Emergency|State of Emergency]].
*an [[Crossing the Rubicon (album)|album]] by Swedish melodic metal band [[Armageddon (band)|Armageddon]]
*title of [[Crossing the Rubicon (Ruppert)|a 2004 book]] by [[Michael Ruppert]] on the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]]
*title of [[Crossing the Rubicon (Mohan)|a book]] by [[C. Raja Mohan]] on [[India]]n [[foreign policy]]
*title of [[Crossing the Rubicon (Kaufman)|a book]] by [[Julie Kaufman]] on human-animal relationships
*title of [[Crossing the Rubicon (Laham)|a book]] by [[Nicholas Laham]] on [[Ronald Reagan]]'s [[Middle East]] [[foreign policy]] 
*title of [[Crossing the Rubicon (Yuan)|a book]] by [[Nathans Y. Yuan]] about a [[China|Chinese]] [[immigrant]] family
*referenced in [[Better Version of Me]] by [[Fiona Apple]] on [[Extraordinary Machine]]
